  "description": "An ideal is a special kind of subset of a ring — one that is closed under addition and that \u0026ldquo;absorbs\u0026rdquo; multiplication by any element of the ring. More precisely, a subset II of a ring RR is an ideal if it is an additive subgroup of (R,+)(R, +) and for every r∈Rr \\in R and every a∈Ia \\in I, both rara and arar belong to II. The absorption property is what distinguishes ideals from mere subgroups: you can multiply an ideal element by anything in the ring and stay inside the ideal.\n",
  "name": "Ideal",
